## Latent risks (NOT bugs, NOT actioned)

- `SIGNAL_MIN_BARS == Z_WINDOW == VOLUME_Z_WINDOW == 20`: implicit coupling with
  no guard. Self-protecting today (if the z-window exceeded the gate, EntryZ would
  be NaN → `_entry_side` returns None → no signal, never a wrong trade). After the
  F1 fix it can no longer cause contamination either. Latent fragility / clarity
  issue only.
- Research-indicator windows are hardcoded literals (`20`/`5`/`14`) rather than
  named params. Values are correct and internally consistent; pure maintainability.
- Dormant unused library functions: `rolling_adf_pvalue`, `ma_slope`, `momentum`.
  Not wired into the strategy or research, so cannot cause runtime bugs.
  Correction to an earlier note: `ma_slope` and `momentum` DO have full tests
  including causality tests in `test_trend.py` — they are not under-tested, just
  unwired.

## Design opinion for Codex to weigh (architecture, not a defect)

This is the one thing I'd argue should have been built differently. Stated as
opinion — Codex should push back if it disagrees.

Root observation: the repo handles "don't bleed across session boundaries" with
TWO inconsistent conventions:
- Functions that take `session` and group internally: `session_atr`,
  `rolling_zscore`, `robust_zscore`, `gap_free_rolling_window`, `cumulative_delta`.
- Functions that are session-agnostic and rely on the CALLER to wrap them:
  `realized_volatility`, `efficiency_ratio`, `adx`, `kyle_lambda`,
  `rolling_autocorr`, `rolling_variance_ratio`.
Both F1 (efficiency_ratio) and F2 (adx) were in the second group — the caller
forgot to wrap.

I do NOT think the fix is "make `session` a required arg everywhere." That would
push a trading concept (sessions) down into the shared-math layer, violating the
repo's founding rule "shared math, not shared trading context." `realized_volatility`
should be computable on any return series and should not know what a session is.

So my opinion is: the convention is fine; the missing piece is a safety net that
does not compromise the principle. Two changes would do it:
1. Make "unscoped" visible at the call site by extending the `_cross_session`
   naming idiom the repo ALREADY invented in `zscore.py` (`rolling_zscore` vs
   `rolling_zscore_cross_session`) to every session-agnostic indicator. A reviewer
   then sees `efficiency_ratio_cross_session(...)` in the wiring and immediately
   asks "should this be scoped?"
2. Replace the per-column reset tests with ONE parametrized test that iterates
   over every `RESEARCH_INDICATOR_COLUMN`, mutates session 1, and asserts session
   2 is unchanged — with an explicit allowlist for any column that is
   intentionally cross-session. This would have failed the day F1/F2 landed and
   cannot be "forgotten" the way a hand-written per-column test was for
   efficiency_ratio and adx.

Smaller, lower-priority opinions:
- Derive the warmup from the window — e.g. `SIGNAL_MIN_BARS = Z_WINDOW` (or
  `max(Z_WINDOW, ...)`) — so the gate cannot silently drift out of step with the
  z-score window. Two independent constants that "happen to be 20" is the smell.
- Promote the hardcoded research windows to named params, mainly so a future
  window sweep is a one-line change and the magic-number coupling is removed.
- Mark dormant library functions as "built, not yet wired" so nobody assumes they
  have been exercised on real data.

I am not implementing any of this. It is here so Codex has the full picture and
can agree, disagree, or counter-propose.
